          <mj-spacer height="30px" />
          <mj-text mj-class="green h2">Hacker Releases Decryption Key for Apple's Secure Enclave Firmware</mj-text>
          <mj-image src="https://image.slidesharecdn.com/rootedconfinal2-150306062334-conversion-gate01/95/demystifying-apple-pie-touchid-43-638.jpg?cb=1425636074"></mj-image>
          <mj-text>A hacker who goes online only by the pseudonym of Xerub has released the decryption key for Apple's Secure Enclave Processor (SEP) firmware.</mj-text>
          <mj-text>The leak, confirmed by an Apple employee who wanted to remain anonymous, is crucial to iOS security, as it now allows hackers and security researchers alike access to a previously encrypted iOS component.</mj-text>
          <mj-text>This key allows someone to decrypt the SEP firmware. It does not allow a third-party to decrypt and access TouchID or other data passing through SEP. Xerub's discovery is not inherently dangerous in itself, but through the ripples caused in the world of iOS security. A publicly available SEP decryption key will allow hackers, surveillance companies, and others to analyze and look for bugs in an area of iOS devices they previously had not had access to.</mj-text>
          <mj-button mj-class="bg-green" href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/hacker-releases-decryption-key-for-apples-secure-enclave-firmware/">
            Read More
          </mj-button>
          <mj-button mj-class="bg-green" href="http://www.techrepublic.com/article/hacker-claims-to-have-decrypted-apples-secure-enclave-destroying-key-piece-of-ios-mobile-security/">
            Even More
          </mj-button>
        </mj-column>
